SIMPLE: squib
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Squib
<hw>Squib</hw> <pr>(skw⟦icr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>squippen</ets>, <ets>swippen</ets>, to move swiftly, Icel.
<ets>svipa</ets> to swoop, flash, dart, whip; akin to AS.
<ets>swipian</ets> to whip, and E. <ets>swift</ets>, a. See
<er>Swift</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little pipe, or
hollow cylinder of paper, filled with powder or combustible matter, to
be thrown into the air while burning, so as to burst there with a
crack.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lampoons, like <qex>squibs</qex>, may make a present blaze.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The making and selling of fireworks, and <qex>squibs</qex> . . .
is punishable.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A kind of slow match or safety
fuse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sarcastic speech or publication; a petty lampoon;
a brief, witty essay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who copied his <qex>squibs</qex>, and reechoed his jokes.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A writer of lampoons.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>squibs</qex> are those who in the common phrase of the
world are called libelers, lampooners, and pamphleteers.</q>
<rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A paltry fellow.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squib</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Squib
<hw>Squib</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Squibbed</conjf> <pr>(skw⟦icr⟧bd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Squibbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To throw squibs; to
utter sarcastic or severe reflections; to contend in petty dispute;
<as>as, to <ex>squib</ex> a little in debate</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squid</ent>⟦br⟧
